<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-186-092  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 186 092.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Engineering  March 1989 v21 n3 p23(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Healthcare information systems provide strategic businessplanning.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jones, Charles.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The major differences between existing healthcare informationsystems and systems for other industries is reviewed.andP;  Theimplications of these differences are analyzed in respect to shortto intermediate strategic as well as long term strategic planning.andO;The healthcare base system helps maintain admitting, transferringand discharging patients, managing medical records, orderprocessing and all financial records.andP;  The base system is the coreupon which profitable MIS can be developed and used.andP;  The numberof operations performed is not as important as how profitable theyare to the hospital.andP;  The system to perform these calculations maybe a mainframe or minicomputer or a combination of them with anynumber of attached subsystems.andP;  A state of the art informationsystem is one that works as a real-time, on-line system from whichinformation is available instantly any time of the day or night.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Hospital Information SystemsInformation SystemsComparisonStrategic PlanningCost Benefit AnalysisGuidelinesSystem SelectionMIS.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>